# Contest 2 Round 3

---

## Problem 1: Cheat 

**Problem Statement** 

As the saying goes... Genshin Impacts your life. Everyone was too busy playing to study for the TOK test and it turns out that only a couple people actually know the answers! But being resourceful IB students, they turn to their last hope: cheating.

There are n students in the class, numbered from 1 to n. Out of the n students, k students actually studied, while the rest of the students cheat. Each cheater copies off exactly one other student, no matter if that person is legitimate or a cheater, with 100% accuracy. This means that students can essentially form "copying chains" where everyone in the chain gets the same mark. 

Each of the k students who studied will receive a mark out of 100, while everyone who copied them (or were in the "copying chain") will receive the same mark. Students who did not study and did not copy off others will receive a 0 for their academic honesty. In the event that the only students in the "copying chain" are cheaters, all the students in the chain receive a score of 0 for playing Genshin Impact and not studying. 

Find the average (mean) score of the students.

**Input Specifications** 

The first line contains 3 space separated integers: n = 10000, the number of students, k = 100, the number of students who actually studied, and c = 5000, the number of instances of students copying off other students.

The next k lines consist of 2 space separated integers: s, the number of the student (from 1 - n) and m, their mark out of 100.

The final c lines will contain 2 space separated integers: a and b, where student a copies off of student b.

It is guaranteed that legitimate students will not copy off anyone else as they are academically honest students. 

It is also guaranteed that each person copies off a maximum of one other person because despite having two eyes, IB students only have one working eye.

**Output Specifications** 

An integer denoting the first three digits of the average (mean) score of the students. Add trailing zeroes if necessary.

**Sample Input** 
```
10 3 6

1 100

4 97

5 89

2 1

3 7

7 9

9 7

8 5

10 8
```

**Sample Output** 

564

**Explanation** 

Student 1 received 100.

Student 2 copied off of Student 1 and also received 100.

Student 3 copied off student 7, who copied off of student 9, who copied off student 7 who did not study and thus received 0.

Student 4 received 97.

Student 5 received 89.

Student 6 did not copy anyone and received 0.

Student 7 copied off of student 9, who copied off of student 7 who did not study and thus received 0.

Student 8 copied off of student 5 and received 89.

Student 9 copied off of student 7, who copied off of student 9 who did not study and thus received 0.

Student 10 copied off of student 8 who copied off of student 5 and thus received 89.

The mean of the scores: 100, 100, 0, 97, 89, 0, 0, 89, 0, and 89 = 56.4. The first three digits as an integer is 564.

<details>
<summary>Click here to view the Java solution.</summary>
<br>

```java
package Cheat;

import java.util.*;
import java.io.*;

public class Solution {

	static BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in));
    static StringTokenizer in;
	
    static int parent[];
    
    static int find(int i) {
    	if(parent[i] == i) {
    		return i;
    	}
    	else {
    		parent[i] = find(parent[i]);
    		return parent[i];
    	}
    }
    
    static void join(int a, int b) {
    	parent[find(a)] = parent[find(b)];
    }
    
	public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException{
		
		int n = readInt();
		int k = readInt();
		int c = readInt();
		
		int[] score = new int[n+1];
		parent = new int[n+1];
		
		for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
			parent[i] = i;
		}
		
		for(int i = 0; i < k; i++) {
			score[readInt()] = readInt();
		}
		
		for(int i = 0; i < c; i++) {
			join(readInt(), readInt());
		}
		
		for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
			score[i] = score[find(parent[i])];
		}
		
		int sum = 0;
		
		for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
			sum += score[i];
		}
		
		System.out.println((double)sum/n);
	}
	
	static String next() throws IOException {
        while (in == null || !in.hasMoreTokens())
            in = new StringTokenizer(br.readLine());
        return in.nextToken();
    }
    
    static long readLong() throws IOException {
        return Long.parseLong(next());
    }
    
    static int readInt() throws IOException {
        return Integer.parseInt(next());
    }
    
    static double readDouble() throws IOException {
        return Double.parseDouble(next());
    }
    
    static char readChar() throws IOException {
        return next().charAt(0);
    }
    
    static String readLine() throws IOException {
        return br.readLine();
    }
}
```

</details>

## Problem 2: Scoring 

**Problem Statement**

Olivia is an avid soccer player, but she also needs to get the attention of scouting agencies so that she can be drafted to the national team. She decides that the best way to put on a show is to try and record as many points as possible. 

There are 10 positions where Olivia can be on the field, labelled 1 through 10. Olivia is given n queries by her coach denoting two connected positions and the time it takes to run from one position to the other. She is allowed to move positions in either direction if the two positions are connected.

Olivia always starts at position 1 on the field but can score if she reaches position 10, from which she will receive a pass instantaneously from her teammate to score. Furthermore, if she is in a position which is connected to position 10, she can pass the ball to her teammate at position 10 instantaneously to score an assist. When a goal is scored, the entire position resets and Olivia starts back at position 1. She can then go for more points.

Olivia only has 90 minutes to get as many points as possible. Each goal is worth 3 points while each assist is worth 2. What is the maximum amount of points that Olivia can score?

Note: The only thing that takes time is Olivia running between positions. Scoring, passing, and restarting at position 1 all are instant.


**Input Specifications**

The first line will have one integer n = 16 denoting the number of connections between different positions.

The next n lines will contain 3 space-separated integers each: p1, p2 and p3, denoting two positions and the number of seconds it takes to run between the two positions.

**Output Specifications** 

Output a single integer denoting the maximum amount of points Olivia can score.

**Sample Input** 

6

1 2 4

1 3 3

2 4 5

3 4 6

4 5 8

**Sample Output** 

Hmmm. It seems to be missing. What gives?!

**Explanation**

There will be no sample output for this test case as it would make the problem too easy... figure it out yourself.

However, if you draw the paths out, you can see the following:

If Olivia decides to run to positions 1, then 3, then 5, it will take her 10 seconds to score. Similarly, if she decides to run to position 1, then 3, it will take her 3 seconds to make an assist. Do with that information how you wish.

<details>
<summary>Click here to view the input string.</summary>
<br>

```
16
1 2 2
1 3 4
2 4 7
2 5 6
3 1 4
3 6 2
4 5 6
4 4 6
5 7 3
5 8 7
6 7 5
6 9 9
7 8 8
7 9 7
8 10 11
9 10 12
```
</details>

<br>

<details>
<summary>Click here to view the correct answer.</summary>
<br>

```
720
```

</details>
<br>

<details>
<summary>Click here to view the Java solution.</summary>
<br>

```java
import java.util.*;
import java.io.*;

public class Solution {

	static BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in));
    static StringTokenizer in;
	
	public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException{
		
		int n = readInt();
		
		int[][] adj = new int[11][11];
		Vertex[] vertexes = new Vertex[11];
		

		Set<Integer> sptSet = new HashSet<Integer>();
		Queue<Vertex> nextVertex = new PriorityQueue<Vertex>(new orderDistance());
		
		for(int i = 1; i < vertexes.length; i++) {
			vertexes[i] = new Vertex(i, Integer.MAX_VALUE);
		}
		
		for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
			int a = readInt();
			int b = readInt();
			int t = readInt();
			
			adj[a][b] = t;
			adj[b][a] = t;
		}
		
		vertexes[1].updateDistance(0);
		nextVertex.add(vertexes[1]);
		
		while(sptSet.size() < 10) {
			int v = nextVertex.peek().number;
			int dist = nextVertex.peek().distance;
			sptSet.add(v);
			nextVertex.poll();
			
			for(int i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
				if(adj[v][i] > 0) {
					if(!sptSet.contains(i) && dist + adj[v][i] < vertexes[i].distance) {
						vertexes[i].updateDistance(dist + adj[v][i]);
						nextVertex.add(vertexes[i]);
					}
				}
			}
		}
		
		int goalTime = vertexes[10].distance;
		int assistTime = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
		
		for(int i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
			if(adj[10][i] > 0) {
				assistTime = Math.min(assistTime, vertexes[i].distance);
			}
		}
		
		int[] dp = new int[5401];
		
		for(int i = 1; i <= 5400; i++) {
			if(i >= assistTime) {
				dp[i] = Math.max(dp[i-assistTime] + 2, Math.max(dp[i-1], dp[i]));
			}
			if(i >= goalTime) {
				dp[i] = Math.max(dp[i-goalTime] + 3, Math.max(dp[i-1], dp[i]));
			}
		}
		
		System.out.println(dp[5400]);
	}
	
	static String next() throws IOException {
        while (in == null || !in.hasMoreTokens())
            in = new StringTokenizer(br.readLine());
        return in.nextToken();
    }
    
    static long readLong() throws IOException {
        return Long.parseLong(next());
    }
    
    static int readInt() throws IOException {
        return Integer.parseInt(next());
    }
    
    static double readDouble() throws IOException {
        return Double.parseDouble(next());
    }
    
    static char readChar() throws IOException {
        return next().charAt(0);
    }
    
    static String readLine() throws IOException {
        return br.readLine();
    }
}

class Vertex{
	int number;
	int distance = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
	
	public Vertex(int number, int distance) {
		this.number = number;
		this.distance = distance;
	}
	
	void updateDistance(int distance) {
		this.distance = distance;
	}
}

class orderDistance implements Comparator<Vertex>{
	public int compare(Vertex o1, Vertex o2) {
		return o1.distance - o2.distance;
	}
}
```

</details>

## Problem 3: Lineup

**Problem Statement**

Alice is standing in a very long line at the DMV, waiting for her driver's license registration. It just so happens that she's been waiting 10 hours, and being bored, she creates a puzzle for you. 

There are n people standing in line from left to right. She finds that by looking to the left of the line, she can see someone if and only if all the people between her and the other person are shorter than the other person (but not necessarily her). Same goes for the right.

In other words, when looking to the left, person ni can see person nj if ni - 1 < nj and ni - 2 < nj and . . . nj + 1 < nj.

Likewise, when looking to the right, person ni can see person nj if ni + 1 < nj and ni + 2 < nj and . . . nj - 1 < nj.

Being very considerate and empathetic, Alice then wonders about the other people in line, so she poses you the following question: What is the average (mean) number of people each person standing in line can see when looking both to the left and to the right?

**Input Specifications**

The first line has an integer n, the number of people in line.
The second line contains n space separated integers.

**Output Specifications**

An integer representing the first three digits of the average (mean) number of people each person standing in line can see. Add trailing zeroes if necessary.

**Sample Input**

5

3 1 4 2 5

**Sample Output**

280 

**Explanation** 

There are 5 people standing in a line.

Person 1 can see person 2 (height 1) and person 3 (height 4) to their right, but cannot see person 4 (height 2), because person 3 is taller than person 4. Person 1 can, however, see person 5 to their right (height 5), as they are tall enough to not be blocked by anyone. Person 1 has nobody to their left. Therefore, person 1 can see 3 people.

Person 2 can see person 3 (height 4) to their right, but cannot see person 4 (height 2), because person 3 is taller than person 4. Again, person 2 can, however, see person 5 (height 5), as they are tall enough to not be blocked by anyone. Person 2 can also see person 3 to their left. Therefore, person 2 can see 3 people.

Person 3 can see everyone to their left and right. Person 3 can see 4 people.

Person 4 can see only person 3 to their left and person 5 to their right. Person 4 can see 2 people.

Person 5 can see person 4 and person 3, but cannot see person 1 or person 2 as they are blocked by person 3. Person 5 can see 2 people.

Taking the average: (3 + 3 + 4 + 2 + 2) / 5 = 2.8. The first two digits are 2, 8, and 0, so the answer is 280.


<details>
<summary>Click here to view the Java solution.</summary>
<br>

```java
import java.util.*;
import java.io.*;

public class Solution {

	static BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in));
    static StringTokenizer in;
	
 	public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException{
		
		int n = readInt();
		int[] heights = new int[n];
		int[] ans = new int[n];

		for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
			heights[i] = readInt();
		}
		
		Stack<Integer> mt = new Stack();
		
		for(int i = n-1; i >= 0; i--) {
			ans[i] += mt.size();
			while(!mt.isEmpty()) {
				if(heights[i] >= mt.peek()) {
					mt.pop();
				}
				else {
					break;
				}
			}
			mt.push(heights[i]);
		}
		
		mt.clear();
		
		for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
			ans[i] += mt.size();
			while(!mt.isEmpty()) {
				if(heights[i] >= mt.peek()) {
					mt.pop();
				}
				else {
					break;
				}
			}
			mt.push(heights[i]);
		}
		
		double sum = 0.0;
		for(int i : ans) {
			sum += (double)i;
		}
		
		System.out.println((double)sum/n);
		
		
	}
	
	static String next() throws IOException {
        while (in == null || !in.hasMoreTokens())
            in = new StringTokenizer(br.readLine());
        return in.nextToken();
    }
    
    static long readLong() throws IOException {
        return Long.parseLong(next());
    }
    
    static int readInt() throws IOException {
        return Integer.parseInt(next());
    }
    
    static double readDouble() throws IOException {
        return Double.parseDouble(next());
    }
    
    static char readChar() throws IOException {
        return next().charAt(0);
    }
    
    static String readLine() throws IOException {
        return br.readLine();
    }
}

```
